VThe rains are here and so is the music to go with the mood. Beginning today, get prepared to treat yourself to Rabindra Sangeet, a rare violin concert by three generations of women, and daylong concerts featuring vocalists from the Kirana gharana, an\u000ad rendering of Dikshitar kritis.Toto Funds the Arts in association with Ananya is inaugurating its series of Chamber Music Concerts with a Rabindra Sangeet recital by Madhusree Baral today.Madhusree will be accompanied on the tabla by Dr. Shanto Ghosh. The concert is at the Ananya Sabhangana, 91/2, 4th Main, Malleswaram, at 6.45 p.m.***Shri Rama Kala Vedike is holding its annual programme on May 9 at Ravindra Kalakshetra.The morning session, starting 9.30 a.m. will feature artistes of the Kirana gharana &#8212; Vaishnavi Hanagal Talkad (Mumbai) in a Hindustani vocal concert, Pandit Naganatha Wadiyar (Hubli) in a Hindustani vocal, child prodigy Master Goutam Hebbar (Bangalore) in a bansuri concert, and Pandit Kaivallya Gurav (Dharawad) in a Hindustani vocal concert. The evening session, starting 6 p.m. will feature Satyajit Talwalkar (Mumbai) in a tabla solo, followed by a felicitation to Vidushi Dr. N. Rajam (renowned violin artiste &#8211; Mumbai) with &#8220;Kalaa Shrunga&#8221;, an annual award of our trust.A rare violin trio comprising three generations of artistes &#8212; Vidushi Dr. N. Rajam, her daughter Sangeetha Shankar, and granddaughter Nandini Shankar will be the highlight of the evening. Admission is free.***Ananya GML Cultural Academy has organised a special day long music programme this Sunday. Ananya &#8220;Sampradaya&#8221;, a festival celebrating the Kannada translation of Subbarama Dikshitar&#8217;s &#8220;Sangeetha Sampradaya Pradarshini&#8221; by Anandarama Udupaa, will be held on May 10 between 9.30 a.m. and 8.30 p.m. at the Bangalore Gayana Samaja. This is in continuation with the publication of &#8220;Sangeetha Sampradaya Pradarshini&#8221; and &#8220;Prathamabhyasa&#8221; published by Ananya. &#8220;Sangeeta Sampradaya Pradarshini&#8221;, a Telugu book authored by Vidwan Subbarama Dikshitar is considered a milestone in the history of Carnatic music. The Kannada translation of this magnum opus has been brought out by Ananya and edited by Vidwan Anandarama Udupa under the guidance of late Prof. S.K. Ramachandra Rao.The programme will feature a rendering of kritis of Muthuswamy Dikshitar, lectures by leading exponents of Carnatic music, a multimedia presentation on the life and music of Muthuswamy Dikshitar, vocal recital by two winners of the national level competition of singing kritis of Dikshitar.   The programme will end with a vocal recital by Vidwan T.M. Krishna.
